1 Introduction

In this project, we are going to analyze the world happiest report. From this report, we are going to try to analyze how can we determine a country with highest level of "happiness". We are going to visualize the data and examine the relationship between each factors that will influence the happiness.

1.1 Import Library¶

  • math: Math library that helps with the calculation
  • sklearn: Efficient tools for predictive data analysis
  • pandas (pd): Use dataframes to import, view, and analyze the data.
  • numpy (np): Perform necessary math operations over the data.
  • matplotlib.pyplot (plt): Create plots for data analysis.
  • Seaborn (sns): Create plots for data analysis

2 Data

2.1 Source of data¶

The data we are going to use in this report is from: https://www.kaggle.com/ajaypalsinghlo/world-happiness-report-2021

The original data for this dataset is from: https://worldhappiness.report/

In this dataset, there are two csv files, which contain world happiest data from past years and this year.

2.2 Explanation of Terms¶

All of the following data explanations are from Official FAQ website

Life Ladder(Ladder score): Measurement of happiness from value from 0 to 10. According to the official, the dataset has a sample size of 2,000 to 3,000 at the national level.

There are six factors that are measured to form the result of Life Ladder:

  • Log GDP per capita: A measurement of the economy growth of a country.
  • Life expectency: An estimation of number of years that a person can live.
  • Generosity: A measurement of people's kindness level.
  • Social Support: A social system that provides people with assistence and comfort.
  • Freedom: The power or right to act, speak, and think as one wants.
  • Corruption: Misconduct or illegal behaviors of people in power.

2.3 Import data and preview¶

To start with the project, we need to load the data from the dataset. To concat the data from 2021 and past years, we rename some of the columns. Those data are loaded into 3 dataframes:

  • data_2021: data from the 2021 report file
  • data_historical: data from the past years report file
  • df: Combined data of data_2021 and data_historical with main information
In [2]:
# Load data from csv
data_historical = pd.read_csv("dataset/world-happiness-report.csv")
data_2021 = pd.read_csv("dataset/world-happiness-report-2021.csv")

# Tranfrom data of 2021's format to historical
data_2021 = data_2021.rename(columns={
    "Ladder score": "Life Ladder", 
    "Logged GDP per capita": "Log GDP per capita", 
    "Healthy life expectancy": "Healthy life expectancy at birth"
})

# Set year
data_2021['year'] = 2021

# Concat dataframes
data = pd.concat([data_historical, data_2021])

# Pick columns we need
df = data[[
    "Country name", "year", "Life Ladder", "Log GDP per capita", "Social support", 
    "Healthy life expectancy at birth", "Freedom to make life choices", "Generosity", "Perceptions of corruption"
]]

# Drop the rows with NaN
df = df.dropna()

# Filter out countries that stay within the top 50 Life Ladder score 
# for at least 15 years of the time period during 2005-2021
total = []
res = []
unique = []

for i in range(2005, 2022):
    for ele in list(top50[i]):
        total.append(ele)

# filter out a unique list from all counries
unique = np.unique(total)
for e in unique:
    if total.count(e) >= 15:
        res.append(e)

print(f"There are {len(res)} countries that stay within the top 50 Life Ladder score for at least 15 years.")

There are 18 countries that stay within the top 50 Life Ladder score for at least 15 years.
In [13]:
plot = []
count = 0

# build a list for rankings of countries each year, 
# use nan to represent years that these countries are not in top50.
for country in res:
    tmp = []
    for i in range(2005, 2022):
        if len(list(np.where(top50[i] == country)[0])) > 0:
            tmp.append(list(np.where(top50[i] == country)[0])[0])
        else:
            tmp.append(math.nan)
    plot.append(tmp)

# Use a line plot to show the trend of countries Ladder Score, 
# and label each line with corresponding country
# nan will not show up on the graph
x = list(range(2005, 2022))
plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = [18, 8]
for y in plot:
    plt.plot(x, y, label=res[count])
    count += 1
plt.legend()
Out[13]:
<matplotlib.legend.Legend at 0x7f2aa4dc8f10>

We can observe from the above dataframe that most countries are not always within top 50 Life Ladder Score. Specifically, ONLY 18 out of 50 countries always stay within top 50 Life Ladder Score, and it means that most countries are not at a "steady" happiness level. The result is computed by excluding 2005 because it's missing almost all data.

Then, according to the plot, most countries that stay within top 50 Life Ladder Score show very unstable rankings. Only a few of them maintain a consistent ranking thoughout 2005-2021.

Given the above two observations, we conclude that it's not easy for countries to stay happy. Therefore, it's meaningful to find out what factors are impacting the Life Ladder score, and what countries should focus on in order to improve or maintain their happiness status.

The next step will be finding out which factor(out of the six factors listed above) has the most noticeable impact on Life Ladder Score.

4 Machine Learning Algorithm

In this section, we will use machine learning algorithm, the linear regression, to create a model to predict the relationship between parmas and life ladder.
This model can help us to know the correlation between these parmaters and the life ladder. What's more, we can also find the impact each paramater.

4.1 Data Preparing¶

Before using linear regression model to predict the result, we need to preprocess the data so that we can feed them into our model.
Since we want to figure out the impact of each paramater, we need to scale (standardize) them into same range.

In [15]:

keys = [
    "Log GDP per capita", "Social support",

scaler = preprocessing.RobustScaler()

4.2 Fit The Model¶

In this section, we will use Linear Regression to fit a model based on our dataset.

In [17]:
linear_regressor = linear_model.LinearRegression()
# Regression based on training dataset
linear_regressor.fit(X_train, Y_train)

# Test accuracy on both training and testing dataset
accuracy_train = linear_regressor.score(X_train, Y_train)
accuracy_test = linear_regressor.score(X_test, Y_test)

print(f"The accuracy on training dataset is {accuracy_train:.4f}")
print(f"The accuracy on testing dataset is {accuracy_test:.4f}")

The accuracy on training dataset is 0.7547
The accuracy on testing dataset is 0.7293

Because the accuracy on the both training and testing dataset is higher than 0.7, our model can indicate the relationship between params and the life ladder with high confidence.

)

Then, a residue plot can help use to know whether our model can effectively interpret the data.

In [20]:
# Get residues
train_residue = linear_regressor.predict(X_train) - Y_train
test_residue = linear_regressor.predict(X_test) - Y_test

# Use histplot to plot them
sns.histplot(train_residue, kde=True, label='train_residue', color='tab:blue')
sns.histplot(test_residue, kde=True, label='test_residue', color='tab:red')

# Add plot descriptions
plt.xlabel("Resdiual")
plt.ylabel("Density")
plt.title("Residuals over train and test dataset", size=20)
plt.legend()
plt.show()

From this plot, we can find that both train residue and test residue follow a normal distribution centered at 0. This indicates that our model can explain the outcome effectively.

5 Conclusion

From the graphs and analysis, we can see that for countries in the Western Europe, they have the highest happiness (Life Ladder) score. In contrast, those countries in Sub-Saharan Africa has the lowest happiness score.

Among all the factors that is considered while measuring the happiness data, GDP plays the most important role, along with social support and life expectency.
